            "paperAbstract": {
                "fragments": [],
                "text": "This paper describes the results of our work in designing a system for large-vocabulary word recognition of continuous speech. We generalize the use of context-dependent Hidden Markov Models (HMM) of phonemes to take into account word-dependent coarticulatory effects, Robustness is assured by smoothing the detailed word-dependent models with less detailed but more robust models. We describe training and recognition algorithms for HMMs of phonemes-in-context. On a task with a 334-word vocabulary and no grammar (i.e., a branching factor of 334), in speaker-dependent mode, we show an average reduction in word error rate from 24% using context-independent phoneme models, to 10% when using robust context-dependent phoneme models."
            },
            "slug": "The-role-of-word-dependent-coarticulatory-effects-a-Chow-Schwartz",
            "title": {
